1. Season Spending

Is the amount increasing every year? What is the trend?

  1. The period 2002-2006 was relatively stable with low spending (around 1.5 mld).
  2. The period 2007-2012 was also stable but succeeding spending from the year 2001.
  3. 2013 was the year that the amount spent created a record. With a slow break in 2014, it raised continually.
  4. 2017 was a unique year. Clubs spent the most money cumulatively. This year probably saw lots of transfers.
  5. 2018 started to return probably to the normal amount of spending.
  • Trend line shows a positive slope.
  • Amount spending clearly raised every season.
  • CLubs tend to spend more money on purchasing players.
  • Year 2017 was one of the most expensive.
  • Based on the trend line I would assume that future years (at that time) would have spent around 3.5-4 mld for the season and would not return to values before 2013.

How much money was spent every year in total for players?

  • The year 2017 was overall successful for players in terms of their contract selling, but as well, it also contains multiple high values with an all-time high outlier of more than 200 million (Neymar).
  • According to position, left and right-wingers tend to have high values, but overall, centre-forward or midfield players are also highly valuable.
  • Players between 2001 and 2009 were not able to reach contracts higher than 50 mil.

2. League/Team value and spending

Which leagues are the most valued in terms of the value of players?

  • The Premier League contains most of the highly valued players (this league contain players with the highest valuation in total).
  • All of the leagues are primary main leagues in that particular country:
    • Premier League = UK
    • Serie A = Italy
    • LaLiga = Spain
    • Ligue 1 = France
    • 1Bundesliga = Germany
    • Premier Liga = Russia

Which team purchased the most players or spent the most

  • Teams that buy most of the players, are from the UK league (Chelsea & Man City).
  • Second highest buyers are from the Spanish league (Real Madrid & FC Barcelona).
  • Italy league teams are also close to the top 10 (Juventus, Inter, AC Milan).
  • Bayer Munich has a value of players around 36,76% of the entire German league.

Which team is a farm (selling players)?

Teams with total value of players sold to other teams

  • Monaco is selling more players than buying. It poses as a farm where players after initial purchase or training, gain value and are later sold at higher prices to different teams.
  • FC Porto has a similar situation to Monaco.
  • Real Madrid is selling with almost 50% of the total value of players. Seems to be, that they are balancing their team to have highly valuable players to be in top leagues, but also having a budget by selling players.

Average spending

Teams with average value of players sold and bought to/by other teams

  • This can be a little bit misleading as some teams purchase one player so their average is very high, like in the case of CC Yatai. On the other hand, some teams made lots of "mid-level" purchases like FC Barcelona and thus have almost the same average.
  • In the case of Monaco, it confirms that this team pose as the farm, making lots of "low" level sales with occasional high-level sells.
  • Based on the data, FC Barcelona bought players often from other Spanish teams.

3. Value of the player

What are the top highest valued players?

Career values

  • This showcases players who were bought with high-value contracts during their career. It is their total value across seasons, leagues and teams.
  • Neymar is the most expensive one. Ronaldo is right behind, but still with more than an 80 million gap. Zlatan is in the fourth place with 163 mil. worth of contracts.
  • The players started almost always with lower estimation value, eventually having higher actual value. In total, some of them were after multiple transfers valued very highly e.g. ngel Di Maria, who in total raised his value against estimation up to 1784%.
  • The recorder is also James Rodrgues who raised his value against estimation up to 4994% and against actual value still more than 1632%.

Which players were traded the most and what is their cumulative price?

  • Zlatan was sold most times with the highest cumulative value.
  • The highest number of transactions was 6 transactions (7 occurences in total).
  • Most players were transacted only once.
  • Only 75% quantile of players were transacted more than 2 times.

4. Position

Which positions are most valued?

  • On average left and right-wingers are the most valued.
  • Followed closely with midfield and centre-forward.
  • This is also confirmed by the graph "Amount Spent per Player each Season".

5. Characteristics

What influences player value?

Correlation insights

  • Age does not have a significant linear relationship with the actual transaction value only around 0.14, considered a low correlation.
  • Estimated value is strongly correlated with the actual value, meaning it is a good indicator of what players are actually bought/sold for.
  • I checked the correlation with estimated values in my dataset where I imputed 0 instead of NaN. Correlation with actual value went slightly down but it is still a pretty high correlation.

Age - Average value based on age

Average Amount spend for Age

  1. Players started to have higher value around age 18-19 years and this continues until 27.
  2. After age 27 the average value starts to decrease. This shows that with higher age the value of players goes down (outliers significantly impact the average)..
  3. There was a marked difference for players aged 33 years old. After further examination, it was the effect of one outlier "Cristiano Ronaldo" who was at the age of 33 sold approximately 9 times above the average value of the player with the price of 117 mil.
